items.name: Ningguang
items.description:
Brief

This is a LoRa model of the lovely character Ningguang from Genshin Impact. It was trained basing on anything V3, and works on both anime checkpoints such as OrangeMixs, 9527, counterfeit, and realistic checkpoints such as ChillOutMix. But it is still in development stage and I will continuously upgrading it. Hope you enjoy using my model.

For more info: https://huggingface.co/okingjo/Multi-identifier_LORA_Model

Changing costume

The two costumes in game (the original one and the orchid's evening gown) are included in this model. and you can switch them by prompt:

"ningguang\(genshin impact\)" will give you the original costume.

"ningguang \(orchid's evening gown\) \(genshin impact\)" will give you the orchid's evening gown costume.

And, if you want, add "headonly" to the prompt to remove her clothes.

About training

I`m using Kohya_ss to train the model with handpicked ningguang images from danbooru. I am painter myself so I paid extra attention to make sure that the faces on each of the images match to my impression to the character. Beside, I have also included 360 snapshots from 3D model of Ningguang on both costumes to further improve accuracy. the total quantity is 115.

The training was divided into two phases, first with default learning rate, 20 repeats, and 7 epochs, then another 6 epochs with 1/10 the learning rate.

It looks there is still room for more epochs, but I am afraid of over-training so that`s it. I`ll do more test in the future.

Please feel free to comment and let me know if there are anything you think could improve the training! I`m still learning!

items.name: SCG Embedding Toolkit for Version 1.5 Models - A collection of tools and helpers from my personal kit
items.description:
Over the last 6 months, I've created quite the collection of helper and tool embeds for doing things like fixing faces, pushing realism, creating anime scenes, making subjects smile, or cry, or face the camera, whatever. Rather than creating separate listings for the literal dozens of tools I have, I've decided instead to just create a "master" listing for all of my tools that I can then update whenever I have new tools to add.

Unlike some of my more grand embeddings out there, many of these serve simple purposes and are of limited effect by themselves. Some are little more than funny experiments that turned into something useful, while others were created as helpers as part of a larger project.

I will continue to update this listing as I create more tools. I'm not planning on exposing my ENTIRE toolbox, just the ones I use and share with friends most frequently.

Don't expect a lot of demo images or a lot of fanfare on this listing. This is my toolkit. If you want to use my tools, please, be my guest, but I make no guarantee of results - Sometimes they work great, sometimes they don't, the fun part is finding the best mix to get the results you want!

As with all of my other embeds, my tools are designed to be mixed with my other 1.5 compatible embeds available on my profile page. Mix and match for some really interesting outputs, and follow me here on Civit to be notified when I release new embeddings!

--------

To use these embeddings in AUTOMATIC1111, copy them to your embeddings folder in your stable-diffusion-webui directory. No need to restart, just invoke the embedding from your prompt. Make sure you are using a 1.5 version compatible model or you will get errors!

--------

modelVersions.name: No512 - Remove Annoyances
modelVersions.description: No512 is my attempt to remove the stuff that tends to show up too much and ruins otherwise good output. Think glasses, masks, hats, necklaces and shine. You can still prompt this stuff back in just fine in my experience, this just reduces that tendency for SD to randomly throw this stuff in by itself. It's scope is limited, most of the modern models are good enough at avoiding the annoyances anyway, but it still serves its purpose. YMMV

modelVersions.name: Neg_Realism512
modelVersions.description: Use this embedding in your negative prompt - Neg_realism512 gooses output towards more realistic, nicer, more cinematic style output. Use it when you're attempting hyperreal or photoreal output as a boost. The effect is subtle, but it does work. The samples I used are purposely heavy handed (calling a painting style in the prompt) but it shows what it does. Use it to goose realism!

modelVersions.name: Neg_Anime512
modelVersions.description: Use this embedding in your negative prompt - This embedding boosts anime output. It won't "create" an anime style on its own, but will instead further enhance anime (or really any animated or cartoon style) output. It works well with the anime variants (Av3, WD, BerryMixes, etc.) that I've tested. As with the other tools in my toolkit, the effect is subtle by itself, but its there!

modelVersions.name: Beauty512
modelVersions.description: This embedding just makes people look better. nicer faces, fuller features. Works on males and females both. It can also have an effect on scenes as well, so if you're trying to make ugly awful scenes, best leave this one on the shelf! This may have a tendency to make people strip, so either add "nudity" to your negative prompt or describe the clothing you want your subjects to wear!

modelVersions.name: Awful512
modelVersions.description: Awful512 does what the name implies. It makes things ugly. Has a stronger effect on adult subjects than children. Should work for both males and females without changing sex that I've noticed. I like to use this when creating apocalyptic scenes, or when working with monsters or just want to make a scene look a bit more grungy and dirty. It's subtle, but it works, just like my other tools.

modelVersions.name: Render512
modelVersions.description: This makes subjects look rendered, or "hyper real" - This can give a video game style sheen to your subjects. If you're creating PS5 style "game screenshots" then this tool will help. NOTE - this does NOT mix well with neg_realism512, you've been warned!

modelVersions.name: neg_facelift512
modelVersions.description: Use this embedding in your negative prompt - This embed makes faces nicer and cleaner. Will remove dirt and yuck out of a scene as it works as a beautifier, so don't use it if you're trying to chase ugly, messy, or dirty scenes. I'll be honest, all of the really great models for 1.5 now do a good job of making nice faces already, so this may be of limited benefit compared to the 2.1 version, but still handy to have in the kit!

modelVersions.name: Anime512
modelVersions.description: This embed tries to create a generic anime style. Works best when combined with Neg_Anime512, and is somewhat model dependent on how well it will work. Works great with the Proto*** / Dream*** models, and of course anything even tangentially related to Av3, NAI or WD.

modelVersions.name: Selfie512
modelVersions.description:
-FOR BEST RESULTS USE AT START OF PROMPT-
Selfie512 does as the name implies, it gets your subjects up close, arm up, smiling for the camera. An unfortunate side effect of the embed will sometimes put a cell phone in your subject's hand. You can try negging "cell phone" and "mirror shot", but honestly, it's a quirk of the pose, just reroll if you don't like it. Another thing, sometimes you get selfie sticks. I haven't found a good way to prevent those yet, but thankfully don't happen too often.

modelVersions.name: Portrait512
modelVersions.description:
-FOR BEST RESULTS USE AT START OF PROMPT-

Gets your subject (somewhat) center framed, smiling and the focus of attention. Sometimes generates selfies, but mostly sticks to medium shot portrait style. If you don't like the soft focus for the background, add "blurry" to your negatives.

modelVersions.name: Neg512
modelVersions.description: Neg512 is my attempt at creating a proper negative prompt that makes output nicer without changing styles. Expect richer colors, clearer subjects and less AI weirdness. Based on my excellent Neg_Realism512, all style modifiers have been removed, leaving a negative that can be applied across pretty much any style (yet to find an incompatible style) - As with all my tools, YMMV, but this has become my go-to "always add" negative, which I then supplement with my other negative embeds as needed. This embed should work for any 1.5 derivative model without any problems.

modelVersions.name: Neg_Hands512
modelVersions.description: My take on a hand fixing negative embed. I've noticed a lot of the other hand fixers cause subjects to hide their hands and fingers (typically because they've added the word "hand" and "fingers" to their negative prompt) - Neg_Hands512 works a bit differently - Rather than focusing on messed up hands and fingers and limbs, I instead focus on the negative aspects of those messed up hands, targeting negative words like "stubby, deformed, polydactyl, mangled, amputated.." etc. THIS IS NOT A TRAINED EMBEDDING - Meaning that it shouldn't affect the style of your images. It's also not perfect, you're still going to get the occasional AI hand oddness, but it does help. YMMV, no guarantee of course, but I use it constantly and you should too!

items.name: dvArch - Multi-Prompt Architecture Tuned Model
items.description:
dvArch is a custom trained model that uses three separate trigger words:

dvArchModern

dvArchGothic

dvArchVictorian

Each of the trigger words will create buildings in that style of architecture. You can also use the three trigger words together to generate whole cities in a mix of buildings in those styles.

dvArchInterior is a custom trained model that uses three separate trigger words:

dvArchInteriorModern

dvArchInteriorGothic

dvArchInteriorVictorian

Each of the trigger words will create interior rooms in that style of building. Use "bedroom" "living room" "bathroom" etc to specify type of room.

items.name: TheSabu Style LoRA
items.description:
This model was trained on TheSabu's artstyle/s. There is two versions of this LoRA, A1 and A2. I think setting the weight of the LoRA to 0.6-1.2 works fine, they're pretty flexible.

  • A1 was trained both on their cartoony & realistic art.

  • A2 was trained on only the cartoony style.

Both have tokens to activate them. (Not necessary but helpful)

  • A1= "SabuCartoon" & "SabuRealism"

  • A2= "SabuCartoon"

I personally like both of them, but A1 and A2 do have their differences. A1 is usually more flexible with the style. But both can be tough to tame at times.

I also would suggest using some helping tags like the following depending on which style you're going for when using A1, these are some tag templates that worked well for me.

(put them at the start of your prompt, you can substract from them or add to them if you want, i also recommend changing the weights depending on how your output images look if they look bad or inaccurate)

  • SabuRealism: (SabuRealism:1.5), (realistic:1.3), (realism, hyperrealism:1.3), (oil painting, painterly:1.3), (soft lighting, soft shading:1.2)

  • SabuCartoon: (SabuCartoon:1.5), (cartoon:1.5), (sketch:1.3), (lineart:1.3), (cellshading:1.1), (painterly:1.1)

  • Random Sketch Style Event:

I'd also advise putting (monochrome, greyscale:1.3) in the negatives

Sample images were made using AbyssOrangeMix2_Hard

items.name: Uhmami
items.description:
Uhmami v1.0

This model is a blend of anime-focused models with a semi-realistic aesthetic, combining 3D digital imagery with photography. It allows the use of prompts based on booru tags, similar to the novelai model, resulting in high-quality semi-realistic images.

The model excels at creating images of young women and can even handle NSFW prompts, although it may not be the best at representing explicit sexual content. However, it's just as effective at creating images of men, animals, and landscapes, as seen in the sample images.

One limitation to note is that it may be somewhat limited in its ability to provide female faces for similar prompts. However, in some cases, this can be an advantage in maintaining visual coherence across multiple images.

Usage recommendations:

  • We highly recommend using the negative prompt (low quality:1.4) as it has a tremendous impact on improving the resulting images. You can combine it with other negative prompts to further enhance the result, but this one is essential. Without it, the resulting image may be flat and of poor quality.

  • Because it incorporates anime models, it tends to represent Asian features, but this can be easily avoided by using the appropriate negative prompts.

  • While not necessary, we recommend using VAE, specifically the vae-ft-mse-840000-ema-pruned model, for best results.

  • Additionally, using Clip skip 2 in the configuration can add depth and richness to the resulting images.

I hope you find it both useful and enjoyable to use!

Usage

※ Hibiki's outfits are rather complicated, so I have documented all of her tags here for your reference.  It may not be necessary to use all of them.

Use any or all of these tags to summon Hibiki: hibiki, bright pupils, halo, dog ears, dog tail, goggles on head

For her standard outfit: twintails, hair bobbles, engineering goggles, purple choker, multicolored jacket, black camisole, grey shirt, black shorts, fishnet pantyhose, dog tags

For her cheerleader alt: cheerleader, ponytail, crop top, wing collar, criss-cross halter, pleated miniskirt, pom pom (cheerleading), blue goggles

- Use cheerleader to strengthen or weaken the effect.

- If the stickers appear on incorrect outfits, add star sticker, sticker on face, sticker on arm to the negative prompt.

- If her name tag and collar appear on incorrect outfits, add wing collar to the negative prompt.

Calm expression: [light smile|expressionless], closed mouth

Embarrassed expression: blush, embarrassed, wavy mouth

Weapon: mortar (weapon), rocket, mortar shell, suitcase, M logo

Weight 0.9 - 1.0 should be ideal; the LoRA is very slightly overfit. I will re-train with fewer steps in the near future.

Refer to https://huggingface.co/khanon/lora-training for other Blue Archive characters, training parameters, and datasets.

.5 -.7 weight is recommended, depending on the model and desired effect. You'll have more freedom prompting specific clothing on the lower end, and the upper end gets racier - this LORA doesn't take much encouraging to get horny. Higher end also tends to add some ornate details to environments which can be interesting, and it bakes at the top so be aware.

items.name: Hipoly 3D Model LoRA
items.description:
(日本語は後半にあります)

High-poly 3D Model LoRA

This is a LoRA trained on high-polygon 3D model images.

It can provide clean, high-resolution skin and hair materials, as well as detailed clothing elements.

For those interested, I have compiled the technical insights gained during the training of ver.2 in the following article.

https://note.com/takumi__ncr/n/n21016c358ea5

Changes in 2.0

  • Increased the number of training images

  • Increased the training resolution (ver.1: 768, ver.2: 896)

  • Revised the tagging

    • Removed the trigger word as well

  • Reviewed the training parameters

Improvements in 2.0

  • It can reproduce a more 3D-like texture and stereoscopi effect than ver.1

  • LoRA can be applied without a trigger word

  • The style can be controlled using 3d and realistic tags

    • When added to Positive Prompt, it enhances the 3D feel

    • When added to Negative Prompt, it adds details such as clothing while maintaining the model's art style

  • The issue of eroding the model's art style with tags such as intricate, detailed has been alleviated

Additional information

The effect of LoRA was confirmed using the following my custom merged models:

  • Alstroemeria Mix

  • Bougainvillea Mix

  • Chrysanthemum Mix

High-poly 3D Model LoRA

ハイポリゴン 3D モデル画像を学習した LoRA です。

3D らしいクリーンで高精細な肌・髪の質感や、衣服のディテールを与えることができます。

ver.2 の学習時に得られた技術的知見をまとめましたので、興味がある方は次の記事をご覧ください。

https://note.com/takumi__ncr/n/n2fb9d265ffa9

2.0 での変更点

  • 教師画像を増やしました

  • 学習解像度を向上しました (ver.1: 768, ver.2: 896)

  • タグ付けを見直しました

    • トリガーワードも削除しました

  • 学習パラメータを見直しました

2.0 での改善点

  • ver.1 よりも 3D らしいテクスチャ感、奥行き感が再現できます

  • トリガーワードなしで LoRA を適用することが可能です

  • 3d, realistic タグを使用することで絵柄のコントロールが可能です

    • Positive Prompt に入れた場合、より 3D 感を強化します

    • Negative Prompt に入れた場合、モデルの絵柄を保ちつつ、衣装などのディテールを追加することができます

その他

items.name: Panty pull / Panty drop
items.description:
*Added a slightly refined v2 version purely focusing on "pantypull".

This is a first iteration of a LoRA model trained on a couple hundred photos, that provides a concept in two flavors:

-Pantypull: Pulling down panties with one or both hands

-Pantydrop: Panties dropped down somewhere along the legs without hands involved.

*It still has some quirks, most notably double panties and it often not quite making the distinction between pull and drop when prompted.

I'm looking to expand on these concepts and make them more varied/consistent. While it's almost purely trained on front-facing poses, it can do some generations from the rear as well.

Many thanks to brandnewfakeuser for making the amazing Shirtlift LoRA and also including his training parameters, which are similar to what I have used for this LoRA.

The example images were generated using QGO-10b-fix model.

Additional LoRA used in the examples:

-Shirtlift: https://civitai.com/models/6693/shirtlift-a-lora-for-flashing-tits

-That's my bush!: https://civitai.com/models/6946/thats-my-bush

items.name: Trapped in Wall
items.description:
I hate it when this happens...

For the other side of the wall... https://civitai.com/models/8817/trapped-in-wall-behind

Weights of 0.7 and 0.8 works pretty well for me. I wasn't able to combine it with character embeddings very well. I didn't try all that hard though.

items.name: Theovercomer8's Contrast Fix (SD1.5/SD2.1-768)
items.description:
Now available: SD1.5 version

Tired of SD producing overblown, bright images?

This LORA model is trained using the technique described in https://www.crosslabs.org//blog/diffusion-with-offset-noise

Use it to produce beautiful, high-contrast, low-key images that SD just wasn't capable of creating until now.

Sample images were generated using Illuminati Diffusion v1.0

The LORA was trained using Kohya's LORA Dreambooth script, on SD2.1-768 and SD1.5 with a dataset of 44 low-key, high-quality, high-contrast photographs.

Seeing is believing: On the left is an image without the LORA, on the right is with the LORA.

items.name: Thomas Shelby (Cillian Murphy) 『LoRa』
items.description:
This model doesn't require face restoration, all the images you see above do not use it. I would recommend changing the LORA weighting between 0.7 and 1.3 depending on the distance away from the camera and how close you want it to be to the original images.

I got people saying that my previous model wasn't flexible enough (even though it was) so I had to create generations with different concepts. Here I have included some different prompts that show how flexible this LORA can be.

This LORA was trained with 1500 steps. 15 images, each with 100 steps. I think I used 1 Epoch. I trained on default 1.5 ema-only.

ALL the images you see above were using the default 1.5 ema-only model, nothing special. So you all got no excuses for bad results XD. Feel free to use with other 1.5 models, im sure they will give fantastic results too.

For any private work, please feel free to contact me for more information:

odawgthat@gmail.com
